.TH "socklog" "8" 
.SH NAME
socklog \- small and secure syslogd replacement for use with runit
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]socklog\f[R] [\-rRTU] [unix] [\f[I]path]\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]socklog\f[R] [\-rRT] inet [\f[I]ip]\f[R] [\f[I]port\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]socklog\f[R] [\-rRT] ucspi [\f[I]args\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]socklog\f[R] is run under runit\[aq]s \f[B]runsv\f[R](8), writing
syslog messages it receives from unix domain socket \f[I]path\f[R] or an
inet udp socket \f[I]ip\f[R]:\f[I]port\f[R] through a pipe provided by
\f[B]runsv\f[R](8) to a \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) process.
.PP
\f[B]socklog\f[R] can be run as an ucspi application to listen to an
unix domain stream socket and for more flexible distributed logging.
.PP
If the environment variables $UID and/or $GID are present,
\f[B]socklog\f[R] drops permissions to those ids after creating and
binding the socket (not in \f[I]ucspi\f[R] mode).
.PP
\f[B]socklog\f[R] converts syslog facility and priority information to
names (\f[I]facility\f[R].\f[I]priority\f[R]:) as found in
\f[I]/usr/include/syslog.h\f[R] at compile time if present.
.PP
On solaris \f[B]socklog\f[R] also accepts \f[I]sun_stream\f[R] as first
argument.
Please see the web page for details.
.SH UNIX SOCKET
\f[B]socklog\f[R] [ unix ] [ \f[I]path\f[R] ]
.PP
Starting \f[B]socklog\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]unix\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\f[R] will listen to the unix domain socket \f[I]path\f[R].
If \f[I]path\f[R] is omitted, the default \f[I]/dev/log\f[R] is used.
.PP
The 1st argument may be omitted, default is \f[I]unix\f[R].
.SH INET SOCKET
\f[B]socklog\f[R] inet [ \f[I]ip\f[R] ] [ \f[I]port\f[R] ]
.PP
Starting \f[B]socklog\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]inet\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\f[R] will listen to the inet udp socket
\f[I]ip\f[R]:\f[I]port\f[R].
.PP
If \f[I]ip\f[R] starts with 0, \f[B]socklog\f[R] will bind to all local
interfaces.
.PP
If \f[I]port\f[R] is less or equal 1024, \f[B]socklog\f[R] must be run
by root.
.PP
\f[I]port\f[R] may be omitted, default is 514.
\f[I]ip\f[R] may be omitted, default is 0.
.PP
\f[B]socklog\f[R] prepends \f[I]a.b.c.d:\f[R] to each syslog message it
receives, where \f[I]a.b.c.d\f[R] is the ip address of the connecting
system.
.SH UCSPI MODE
\f[B]socklog\f[R] ucspi [ \f[I]args\f[R] ]
.PP
Starting \f[B]socklog\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]ucspi\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\f[R] will run as an ucspi application.
Normally \f[B]socklog\f[R] will only be started in \f[I]ucspi\f[R] mode
by an ucspi server tool, such as \f[B]tcpsvd\f[R](8),
\f[B]tcpserver\f[R](1) or \f[B]unixserver\f[R].
.PP
For each \f[I]arg\f[R], \f[B]socklog\f[R] will prepend $\f[I]arg\f[R]:
to each syslog message, if the environment variable $\f[I]arg\f[R] is
present (maximum is 8).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R]
raw.
Write the raw syslog messages (no conversion of facility and priority)
to the pipe, additionally to the log messages with syslog facility and
priority converted to names.
.TP
\f[B]\-R\f[R]
raw only.
Same as \-r above, but write the raw syslog messages only.
.TP
\f[B]\-T\f[R]
Drop the timestamp (in classic RFC3164 format, \[dq]Mmm dd
hh:mm:ss\[dq]) in front of the log message; helpful if you add your own
timestamps later.
.TP
\f[B]\-U\f[R]
respect umask.
Don\[aq]t set umask to 0 before creating a unix domain socket, but
respect the current setting of \f[B]umask\f[R](2).
This option only takes effect in unix mode.
